---

<section
  id="problem"
  class="relative z-10 py-24"
  style="background: linear-gradient(180deg, #0a0a1a 0%, #111128 100%);"
  aria-labelledby="problem-headline"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-[1120px] px-6">
    <div class="grid gap-16 md:grid-cols-2 md:items-start">
      <!-- Left: label + headline -->
      <div>
        <p class="reveal mb-4 font-mono text-[0.72rem] font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-brand-electric opacity-80">
          The problem
        </p>
        <h2 class="reveal reveal-delay-1 font-heading text-[clamp(1.8rem,3.5vw,2.75rem)] font-bold leading-[1.15] text-text-primary" id="problem-headline">
          Your community's data deserves more than an afterthought.
        </h2>
      </div>

      <!-- Right: body copy -->
      <div class="reveal reveal-delay-2 flex flex-col gap-5">
        <p class="text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.75] text-text-secondary">
          Most cybersecurity tools are built for enterprises with six-figure budgets
          and dedicated IT teams. Community organizations get the leftovers: complex
          dashboards designed for analysts, pricing that assumes a Fortune 500
          headcount, and language that treats security as a gatekeeping exercise.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.75] text-text-secondary">
          Meanwhile, the organizations doing the most sensitive work—protecting
          member identities, safeguarding health information, coordinating advocacy
          in hostile environments—are left to figure it out alone.
        </p>
        <p class="font-heading text-[1.15rem] font-semibold text-brand-electric">
          We built Secure Pride because we needed it ourselves.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Callout -->
    <div
      class="reveal mt-12 rounded-xl border border-dark-border bg-dark-elevated p-8"
      style="border-left: 3px solid #ff2d95;"
      aria-label="Stakes context"
    >
      <p class="mb-3 font-mono text-[0.7rem] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-brand-hotPink">
        What's actually at stake
      </p>
      <p class="text-[1rem] leading-[1.65] text-text-secondary">
        For a queer youth organization, a compromised donor database doesn't just
        mean a compliance event—it risks outing anonymous contributors. For a gender-affirming
        health clinic, a data breach exposes patients seeking care in states where
        those services are under active political attack. The threat models are
        different. The security approaches need to reflect that.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
